Every bite was fresh, clean, and clearly made with top-tier ingredients and the best nori I’ve ever tasted, no joke. I had a yuzu drink that was bright and citrusy, the perfect pairing for the richness of the fish. Then Sonny surprised us with a matcha-infused sake , something I never knew I needed, but now can’t stop thinking about. The best part? Total heart melter. 🥹💕 Whether you’re a die-hard sushi lover, a sake explorer, or just want to try something new and magical in SLO, Sushi Table is a must. This isn’t just sushi, it’s an experience. As a former pastry chef and having several chef friends at the wedding, we were all flabbergasted this was served as a wedding meal. The catering staff appeared unprepared, did not know the menu, and spoke loudly through the Father of the Bride speech -- something my family and I found incredibly disrespectful. Many dishes were cold, poorly cooked or tasted days old. Some were mislabeled or not labeled at all. My guests had to guess whether they were eating beets or potatoes because the staff didn't know what the gray undercooked vegetables were (they were beets, it turned out). There were no accommodations for dietary restrictions we had discussed repeatedly over months of planning. Some guests went hungry. Some felt unwell later that evening, including myself. We had brunch at Baby Bear Biscuits and that was also a disappointment. The cashier in front was very rude to me, my family, and my guests that were patronizing their business. I trusted Baby Bear Biscuits with one of the most meaningful parts of my wedding day, and that trust was broken. We ordered the grits the fried chicken sandwich and my friend had the vegetarian fried green tomato sandwich and all of them were extremely flavorful without feeling overly greasy or salty. The owner even threw in a slice of sweet potato pie for us after the cashier had trouble getting our order right. We could tell that these are just the start up pains because the food itself was exceptional. And I don’t usually like sweet potato pie, but I ate every bite of this one. I love hot chicken sandos. I am a Hot Ones nut and have tried over a hundred of the hot sauces featured on the show. I’ve been to dozens of different hot chicken spots in Cali and I have to admit, Jay Bird’s is good! I ordered ‘fire,’ the hottest they had to offer. It made my nose run, but was delicious. If you’re a fan of trying the hottest chicken sandwiches, this one won’t kill you. If you’re a newbie, this is Carolina reaper hot. Take heed. My wife had the Mac and cheese topped chicken sandwich and loved it. Our kids love the Mac and cheese. Super creamy and cheesy. Did I mention there is beer right next door? There is! You can also order ‘big sexy style,’ which was described to me as a buffalo sauce. It resembles Hot zones own Buttery Buffalo Sauce. "Lovely cafe in Old farm house setting serving tasty, healthy, and well proportioned meals. You place your order inside at the counter and go find a table. When your number token is activated, you pick up your food from the service window (ingenious way of using an original sash window from the farm house!). Then you sit at picnic tables or at bar height counters to eat. The Barn tacos were the perfect amount of food - 2 street corn tortillas with scrambled eggs, roasted veggies, and a tangy chipotle aioli. Very good! Also got good reviews on the classic breakfast and the avocado toast (generous slice of what looked like homemade bread, and the avocado with some red pepper flakes for some zing). Added to our good ambiance was a low key guitar performer who did not try to overpower the open air space with sound. There were waves of people coming in for breakfast but it never felt crowded or busy so the rush was well managed by the staff. The Big Sheesh sandwich was huge and amazing. The savory Barbacoa meat was incredibly delicious. It was tender, the meat fell apart easily, and had a rich-smoky flavor. This melted burger combines all of the ingredients to help develop and deepen a complex flavor. I really enjoyed it and appreciated the generous portions. However, it was a little too spicy and had a greasy texture for my taste. This burger place used to have very great hot dogs but I no longer see them on the menu. Overall, our dining experience at this restaurant was exceptional, and we liked it.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "I can't recommend Brooks Burgers’ Big Sheesh sandwich highly enough. The Big Sheesh sandwich was huge and amazing. The savory Barbacoa meat was incredibly delicious. It was tender, the meat fell apart easily, and had a rich-smoky flavor. LOVE Bing's Bao Buns. Growing up in a Chinese family, I was raised on bao. And Bing's bao is honestly my favorite I've ever had, anywhere. First, I love the bun thickness to fillings ratio--it's exactly how I personally like them, with the bun not so thick that it overwhelms the flavor of the filling. Second, I love that Bing's always offers a variety of plant-based options for both their bao and additional menu items, including Kimchi Fried Rice. Whether you are vegan, or vegetarian, or not, their plant-based options are just as flavorful and satisfying as anything on their menu. Third, Bing's offers so many amazing items, beyond bao, including Lo Mein Noodles and Tater Tots. I highly recommend the Bing's Seasoning edition of the Tater Tots. It has a very tasty and memorable kick, without being too spicy for those who can't tolerate too much. And on top of all of that, Bing's always has the best customer service. They make you feel truly appreciated for your patronage, and that is important. They are family-owned, and personally, I love getting to support high-quality businesses that are. Plus, they have a wide selection of cool imported snacks, and a wide selection of tasty mochi too, including vegan mochi. I feel they go above and beyond at what they do, and are such a true gem in our Central California Coast. In all of my bao from D.C. to SoCal, I still love the ones here at Bing's in San Luis Obispo the best.", 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': "I LOVE Bing's Bao Buns. I made it clear that I wanted the top stinkiest & flavorful Cheeses & not one, but two people helped me through their rather extensive selections. I would say that their selection rivals or even exceeds some other Cheesemongers in SLO County. I ultimately choose about several items and also tried a few interesting samples as well. Since I had already ordered fresh Bao from one vendor & Curry from the next one, I could not add yet a yummy CCC sandwich to the mix...or could I? I did choose what I could take home for a DIY plate later, including some Serrano Jamon from Spain. This CC Creamery is definitely a great go to Deli, and is even open seven days a week. It would be ideal to get & savor a nice Speck & Shrooms [& Epoisee Cheese] sandwich on another day. I think a good Thai soup from the vendor next door would go with it well. I will definitely find many excuses to come here for all kinds of goodies and fine friendly knowledgable service with a smile. I was working in the area and wanted some nachos, so I got on doordash and ordered $14 Nachos, a $14 burrito for dinner later, and a $5 Horchata (size not advertised and no options). They used a small tray with dividers, placed a couple of chips on top of the dividers, then a few scoops of cheap toppings, hardly any meat. Both the most expensive and lowest quantity nachos I\'ve ever purchased. It\'s better than Taco Bell, but no better than the cheapest nachos in town. Then there was the burrito; it was a gigantic, probably 12" tortilla, with maybe a scoop of rice and half a scoop of vegetables. 90% of it was tortilla, and I don\'t even think it had chicken or pesto in it. (I know, weird combo, but that\'s why I used to like Chilly Peppers). The only positive about the horchata was that it had cinnamon sprinkled on it. Other than that, it was an 8oz cup full of ice and one drink of bland rice water. 'Happened to come across Taste while browsing Yelp and decided to stop in for dinner. The place has a cool vibe—nothing over the top, but definitely not underdone either. You can dress up or keep it casual, which I really appreciate. Food-wise? A bit of a hit and miss, unfortunately. I went with the Trio and ordered the Burger in Paradise, Truffled Up Fries, and Gouda & Chorizo Mac N Cheese. The burger? Solid! The sauce had a great flavor, and the Gouda was a nice touch. The arugula and tomatoes tasted fresh, and the ciabatta bun and meat were cooked perfectly for my taste. The fries? Pleasant surprise! I’m not usually into string fries, but I actually liked these a lot. The truffle wasn’t overpowering, and they came out just right. The Mac N Cheese? Miss. Unfortunately, it lacked flavor. The chorizo felt like an afterthought, and the Gouda didn’t really come through. That said, the noodles were cooked perfectly—just wish the rest delivered. All in all: The service was great, the vibe was on point, and most of the food was well worth the price. The moment we sat down, we were serenaded by Whitney Houston's "I Will Always Love You," setting the perfect tone for the evening. The staff was incredibly welcoming and attentive, making our first visit feel special. I opted for the quartet, allowing me to sample four different items from the menu. The shoestring fries were perfectly crispy, and the sliders were nothing short of amazing. My wife chose the pulled pork slider and a chicken sandwich, both of which she thoroughly enjoyed. However, the highlight of our meal was undoubtedly the dessert and the drinks from the bar. The cocktails were expertly crafted, and the dessert was a delightful way to cap off our dining experience. Overall, Taste Craft Eatery exceeded our expectations with its delicious food, fantastic atmosphere, and attentive service. Will be coming back. I ordered lamb samosas, chai, and the combination dinner plate, which includes your choice of lamb or chicken curry, lentil soup, chicken tikka masala, yogurt, rice pudding, basmati rice, and naan bread. The lamb samosas were delicious, especially when topped with the the provided sauces. I opted for the lamb curry, which was perfectly spiced - very intense and flavorful but not overpowering. The lamb meat itself was very tender and could be parted with a spoon if desired. The lentil soup and chicken tikka masala were equally as good and just as well prepared. Both the yogurt and the rice pudding were new to me, but both were enjoyed. The naan was fluffy and soft, the chai was good, and sugar is provided to taste in packets, including raw cane and artificial sweeteners. Service was great, and very friendly. They had an Indian pop music playlist playing in the restaurant, which I enjoyed despite not understanding. May not be to all tastes, though.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'Great food, great service. Will be coming back. 'places/ChIJlZi1bTrx7IARhKtBpJizsA4/reviews/Ci9DQUlRQUNvZENodHljRjlvT2tsWE1Vd3phRWxNTkZsMGFuQkhNRlJMYkRka05HYxAB', 'relativePublishTimeDescription': '2 weeks ago', 'rating': 5, 'text': {'text': 'In today’s dining landscape, stumbling upon an independently owned burger spot feels almost like finding buried treasure. Chain burger joints dot nearly every block, but their flavors often blur together—predictable, uniform, and lacking the distinctive charm of a true one-of-a-kind eatery. I rarely seek out burgers these days. Still, every so often, nostalgia for the hearty, character-driven burgers I once loved comes calling. On a recent trip to San Luis Obispo, that call was answered—loudly—by Cool Cat Café, a retro-themed diner that not only serves exceptional food but also rekindles the golden days of the 1990s. The moment I stepped inside, with its vintage décor and warm, familiar buzz, I had that instinctive feeling: this place is special. The hospitality matched the setting. Our waitress, whose genuine kindness and attentiveness stood out, treated us as if we were longtime friends rather than first-time guests. Her thoughtful service set the tone for the meal that followed. I ordered the Don Ho Burger, a Hawaiian-style creation crowned with pineapple and my choice of an over-easy egg. The richness of the yolk mingled with the sweetness of the fruit and the smoky savor of the patty—made from fresh, never-frozen beef—to create what I can only describe as a “life-changing” burger. Frankly, it surpassed the Hawaiian burgers I used to swear by at Island Burger. My son opted for Bogy Burger, customized with extra grilled onions and an over-easy egg. He declared it a masterclass in balance—each ingredient playing its role in perfect harmony. My wife, who almost never touches burgers, ordered the Luna Burger with avocado. She initially planned to “just have a taste,” but ended up finishing the entire thing. If that’s not a testament to its flavor, I don’t know what is. Our daughter went for the Hula Chicken Sandwich, adding lettuce, tomato, and an over-hard egg. She loved its freshness and depth—flavors you’d never find at a fast-food chain. The sides were equally impressive: onion rings that were crisp without being greasy, sweet potato fries with a subtle natural sweetness, and golden fries cooked to perfection. And then there was the milkshake—creamy, indulgent, not overly sweet, and the perfect nostalgic finish to our meal. Cool Cat Café is more than just a burger joint. It’s a time capsule of retro charm, a masterclass in quality ingredients, and a place where friendly service turns a great meal into a cherished memory. For anyone longing for the taste and feel of a real, independent burger experience—this is the place. Highly recommended.', 'languageCode': 'en'}, 'originalText': {'text': 'In today’s dining landscape, stumbling upon an independently owned burger spot feels almost like finding buried treasure. The richness of the yolk mingled with the sweetness of the fruit and the smoky savor of the patty—made from fresh, never-frozen beef—to create what I can only describe as a “life-changing” burger. Frankly, it surpassed the Hawaiian burgers I used to swear by at Island Burger. My son opted for Bogy Burger, customized with extra grilled onions and an over-easy egg. He declared it a masterclass in balance—each ingredient playing its role in perfect harmony. My wife, who almost never touches burgers, ordered the Luna Burger with avocado. She initially planned to “just have a taste,” but ended up finishing the entire thing. If that’s not a testament to its flavor, I don’t know what is. Our daughter went for the Hula Chicken Sandwich, adding lettuce, tomato, and an over-hard egg. She loved its freshness and depth—flavors you’d never find at a fast-food chain. The sides were equally impressive: onion rings that were crisp without being greasy, sweet potato fries with a subtle natural sweetness, and golden fries cooked to perfection. And then there was the milkshake—creamy, indulgent, not overly sweet, and the perfect nostalgic finish to our meal. Cool Cat Café is more than just a burger joint. It’s a time capsule of retro charm, a masterclass in quality ingredients, and a place where friendly service turns a great meal into a cherished memory. For anyone longing for the taste and feel of a real, independent burger experience—this is the place. Not many places around here do you see a draft list with Sante Adarius, Alvarado Street, Russian River, Green Cheek, Everywhere, Humble Sea, and Trillium all at the same time. Also source the very best local SLO/Ventura County beers. Staff here is always friendly. They have TVs, weekly events, often bring in local food trucks, and have amazing refrigerated to-go beer selections as well. They're the center piece of the Duncan Alley project for good reason and we look forward to meeting friends for beers + hanging here well into the future. Our top 5 favorite/goto sushi rolls are: Cherry Blossom Roll Hawaiian Roll Dragon Roll Grand Tasty Roll Kumiko Roll We have tried many of their offerings but due to a mild shrimp allergy in the family tend to avoid dishes/sushi rolls with shrimp or at least shrimp that is easy to pick out if the roll for the one family member. The only dish I heard less than positive feedback on from people I know is the baked green muscles, so if this a fav for you maybe don’t order at any of smaller sushi restaurant in SLO. The Kumiko Boat is a excellent choice, if are less of a raw sushi fan, order a extra California, Crunch or spicy tuna roll with it to turn that extra roll into an amazing extra custom rainbow roll for the sashimi pieces, it also comes with 2 midi soups, order more at under $2 ea if a bigger group, and comes with a decent size combo salad that includes seaweed salad, cucumber salad, and in out order what I think was smoked octopus salad, anyway it was delish, and I’m sure subject to chefs choice changes. Sashimi pieces are thick, most if sliced thinner and in half could be used to top 4 basic roll pieces. It is also a nice place to grab a thoughtful last minute yummy gift for the locals. This was my first stop, on my marathon of rescuing, day-old goods, via the "Too Good To Go" program. The lady who helped me was really nice & helpful. It was fairly early on a nice sunny Sunday morning. While I had some trouble with one of my camera systems, I still took a few good shots. It is funny how I notice things better after later looking at the pics. I will have to try again another time, with some of my Macro lens to get some cool close ups of some tasty looking items. I did score a yummy loaf of bread and some pastries which I later munched on at home. The bread is way above what one typically finds and reminds me of European Style loafs that are more of a meal in themselves. This loaf was heavy, hefty, and satisfying, without feeling too dense. The last time I was at this building was when there was another business there. HOB has done a good job with taking it over, and I was generally impressed and really wanted to linger longer, but time was wasting. I still had to pick up & save excess eats at four other places. Later on, the mixing and matching of all sorts of baked goodies was fun. Adding a little butter or jam after toasting some items really enhanced the pleasure...and sadly, the calories. HOB surely has a fairly extensive bakery menu and some interesting breakfast/brunch choices. Lots of items really appealed to me for the future, such as a pie, or bagels.
